                    "company": "The Hospital for Sick Children",
                    "description": "Comatose critically ill neonates and children are at risk for seizures, which have been associated with worse outcomes. Previous studies have identified electrographic seizures in up to 46% of patients and status epilepticus in up to 23% of patients. The majority of electrographic seizures are subclinical, meaning they lack observable clinical manifestations and therefore require continuous electroencephalography (cEEG). Resources are often scarce, so these will be allocated to patients at greatest risk for seizures. Insight into the neurophysiological basis of clinical and subclinical seizures would inform our understanding of their relative severity and potential to cause lasting brain injury. We aimed to test the hypothesis that greater pathological synchronization of distributed brain networks occurs in seizures with clinical manifestations compared to subclinical seizures by means of graph theory. The graph measures clustering coefficient (measure of segregation) and global efficiency (measure of integration) were calculated and compared between groups.  \n\n\u2022 Department of Neurosciences & Mental Health (Research Institute) and Division of Neurology (Hospital)\n\u2022  Daily supervisor: Ben Dunkley, PhD\n\u2022 Assessor: Cecil Hahn, MD, MPH\n\u2022  Report: \"Functional brain network alterations underlying clinical and subclinical seizures in critcally ill neonates and children\" \n\u2022 Grade 8.5/10 including 9 for report\n\u2022  \u201cBrain Network Properties of Clinical versus Subclinical Seizures Among Critically Ill Children\u201d has been pusblished in Clinical Neurophysiology",
                    "title": "Master's Research Internship - Research Project 2",
                    "employment_type": "Full-time"
                }
            ]
